<HEADLINE>
<P>
REBELS CUT OFF RETREAT FOR RWANDAN TROOPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rebels cut off the last avenue of retreat Monday for government troops caught 
in the capital, Kigali, and overran a vital army barracks near Gitarama, the 
interim government's stronghold. 
</P>
<P>
 The interim government retreated to Gitarama, about 25 miles southwest of 
Kigali, ahead of a rebel advance into the capital last month. 
</P>
<P>
 The government's barracks at Nyanza, about 19 miles south of Gitarama, have 
fallen to the rebels, a visit there Monday showed. But the government has not 
fled Gitarama, contrary to rebel claims. 
</P>
<P>
 However, a U.N. source said earlier on condition of anonymity that the fall of 
Nyanza would be seen as a major blow to the army's ability to defend the 
interim government stronghold at Gitarama. 
</P>
<P>
 The rebels' seizure of the Nyanza barracks came as they and the army began 
U.N.-mediated cease-fire talks. U.N. spokesman Abdul Kabia said the sides 
agreed to meet again Thursday. 
</P>
