</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ONE-HITTER STOPS NORTHRIDGE IN TITLE GAME; SOFTBALL: PARRA PITCHES TOP-RANKED 
ARIZONA TO VICTORY IN WOMEN'S COLLEGE WORLD SERIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAIGE A. LEECH, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Arizona ace Susie Parra threw a one-hitter and faced just two batters over the 
minimum Monday to pace the Wildcats to a 4-0 victory over Cal State Northridge 
in the championship game of the Women's College World Series in front of 3,966 
at Hall of Fame Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 Arizona (64-3), which remained top-ranked throughout the season, scored a 
single run in each of the first three innings and never let third-ranked 
Northridge (52-10) into the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Parra surrendered a two-out double to Beth Calcante in the first inning, but 
struck out Tamara Ivie to end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
 Parra, who struck out 13, retired 18 consecutive batters after Calcante's 
double. With two out in the seventh, Ivie drew a full-count walk. Parra 
however, struck out Scia Maumausoloon four pitches to end it. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are happy to be here after all that has happened this year," Northridge 
Coach Gary Torgeson said. "But I have to give Susie Parra credit because she 
changed speeds well and had everything going today." 
</P>
<P>
 It was the third national title in four years for the Wildcats, who defeated 
UCLA in the final last season. Arizona could remain on top for quite a while. 
Only two starters -- Parra (33-1) and third baseman Susie Duarte -- are 
seniors. 
</P>
<P>
 "Today it was all Susie Parra," Arizona Coach Mike Candrea said. "To go out 
after four years like she did with a one-hitter is incredible. To have three 
national titles in her four years, somebody ought to take a look at what she 
has done." 
</P>
<P>
 Pitching a one-hitter against a team that has batted better than .300 all 
season surprised Parra. 
</P>
<P>
 "My changeup was working good and we kept them guessing," she said. "But I was 
shocked to end the year like that." 
</P>
<P>
 Arizona, which was batting .409 as a team in the tournament, had seven hits 
off Jennifer Richardson (9-1) in four innings. Amy Windmiller came on in relief 
in the fifth and retired all six batters she faced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
